															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dysadron" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(4384469); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=4384469&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204880" alt="Dysadron" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=4384469)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dysadron" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(4384469); return false;" >Dysadron</a></span> <span class="odate time_1609374438 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">31 Dec 2020 00:27</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4857810">
									

<p>This is a superbly written tale. I've not encountered the Twisted Pines canon before, but found it incredibly easy to understand what was going on and who the characters were. Indeed, the tale's motivated me to read the canon.</p>
<p>There are some cracking lines and imagery here:</p>
<ul>
<li>&quot;the air is filled with the electric gurgle of a computer that is only barely able to withstand the brunt of an entire human soul.&quot;</li>
<li>The section in which Phinneas &quot;noclips&quot;, exposing the artificial nature of his surroundings.</li>
<li>That ending. The cutting short of Phinneas's final huzzah, bookended by the lyrics, is wonderfully done.</li>
</ul>
<p>It's pieces like this that motivate me to read outside of my comfort zone.</p>

							</div>

								
